    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-06-25T13:44:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-06-25T13:44:00-05:00" n="544"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d544">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.515/69: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hibbard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Monrovia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-06-25T18:00:00-00:44"
                            >June 25, 1942—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 26—8:46 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>213. Legation’s telegram 62, March 1 [<hi rend="italic">8</hi>], 8 [<hi
                        rend="italic">10</hi>] a.m. Finance officer of the American contingent has
                    with him $300,000 worth of American silver coins and proposes to begin payment
                    of troops at the <pb facs="0445" n="433" xml:id="pg_433"/> end of the month. I
                    would appreciate instructions as to whether this sum is to be put into
                    circulation here as the beginning of the substitution of American for British
                    currency as outlined by McBride in the telegram above referred to. In this case
                    arrangements will have to be made for the gradual withdrawal by the bank of
                    British currency. If, however, it is intended to put it in circulation side by
                    side with British currency now here arrangements must be made to have it
                    declared legal tender for all purposes at the rate of $4 to the pound as already
                    suggested.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hibbard</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
